‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
There‚Äôs something romantic about the term ‚Äúmedieval‚Äù even with the connotation of ‚Äúprimitive‚Äù attached to the word. And for me I think of poverty and disease too‚Ä¶
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
But the period from 5th to 15th centuries in Europe is responsible for our fantasies of princes and princesses, damsels in distress and castle drawbridges‚Ä¶ the best preserved of which is probably Carcassonne in France.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
If you want to see a medieval city though, there is none better than Tallinn, first appearing in records in 1219 when Denmark claimed it as their own. Long since the capital of Estonia and a UNESCO site in its entirety, the town is a picture book model of ancient times.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs also thoroughly modern - it has the highest number of start-ups per person among European countries, super fast 5G wifi, and is where Skype and Transferwise were born. It was named a global leader in digital by NatGeo, who say the ‚ÄúE‚Äù of Estonia must mean electronic!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
What‚Äôs the smartest city you‚Äôve been too so far?

üá™üá™ A FAIRYTALE CHRISTMAS üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Where are you spending the holidays this year?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I‚Äôll be heading back to Eastern Europe, to Belgrade, Serbia, for the first time. It‚Äôll be a return to the region after this summer‚Äôs trip to the Baltics.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The highlight in Estonia was this symmetrically stunning castle on the island of Saaremaa, Kuressaare castle. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I wonder how they designed it way back centuries ago, but I guess we have always been attracted by shapes and symmetry.

üá™üá™ THE HUNTING CASTLE üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Don‚Äôt you feel that most of the time architecture from the past is prettier than the glass and concrete boxes we build for ourselves today?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
That‚Äôs what was on my mind looking at this fairytale villa built in 1890 on the island of Saaremaa in Estonia as a little castle for summer hunting holidays. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Initially a private residence it was turned in to boarding school, then a summer hotel. In the years 1930 to 1940 it even opened a vegetarian restaurant which seems part i sultry progressive for the time!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The stones that form the foundation are taken from the huge fortress opposite, the banks of which I‚Äôm sitting upon. Today it‚Äôs fully renovated and known as Ekesparre - right by Kuressaare castle. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ BOGWALKING IN LAHEMAA üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
When you plan to visit a country, what do you look for first?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
For me, I check National Parks, to know what kind of unique landscapes there may be to explore. In Estonia, perhaps the most unusual is the raised bogs of Lahemaa and the 7,000-year-old Laukasoo Reserve. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You have to walk first through a forest to find it, and then there is a trail of 3.5 km over board walks. The bogs are create by water under the earth, making soft ground, and if you step on it, its like a bouncy castle! Soft and springy.

Some parts of course, you can fall straight through, so it‚Äôs dangerous to try stepping on it and recommended to go with a guide as we did with @visittallinn.

You can also try bogshoeing, which are like snowshoes. Then you can walk on the soft and squidgy surface more safely and explore the flora, former sand dunes, eskers, and heath forest. Keep an eye out for the animals that live here too, including a population of boar, red deer, wolves, bear and lynx.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ DIVING IN A PRISON üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The prisoners in the Soviet-era Rummu jail might have been unsure of their future - but I doubt they ever thought the prison complex and quarry they lived in would be come a diving and beauty site!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Home to around 400 inmates, it was established in the 1940s by the Soviet Union, built on the lip of a limestone quarry where the inmates were¬†forced to work.

The prison fell into ruin after the collapse of the USSR, water naturally filling the area until it become a large lake that now covers most of the buildings and infrastructure.¬†It filled up so fast that many of the mining machines and buildings were swallowed whole by the rising waters. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
A beach now sits at the bottom of the quarry. Paddleboarders are able to circle the upper floors of jail and divers can explore it all underwater.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ SUUR T√ïLL AND PIRET üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Norse mythology brought us Thor and Odin, but on the nearby island of Saaremma in Estonia they have their own great heroes. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Carved by Estonian sculptor Tauno Kangro. The sculpture depicts Suur T√µll (the Great T√µll), A giant who tossed huge rocks everywhere, mostly aiming for his archenemy Vanat√ºhi or other enemies of Saaremaa people. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
T√µll was king of Saaremaa but he lived as a common farmer with his wife Piret.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In one Legend, he would head to S√µrve peninsula (with that lighthouse in my previous shots!) from
where he could reach to the island Ruhnu, where he had his cabbage field. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
When his wife Piret started to make a fire under the cauldron, T√µll went through the sea to his cabbage field and came back in just half an hour, so that he could hand Piret the cabbages when the water had just started to boil!

üá™üá™ GETTING BACK TO NATURE üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
One of the beauties of the Baltics is their lack of big cities - or many cities at all. And that means more nature!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Tallinn is surrounded by a variety of landscapes, and national parks. We got up early to begin our exploration at J√§gala Waterfall, which drops across a 50 meter-wide fault just 4km before the river enters into the Gulf of Finland. The morning mist created a timeless ambiance.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Water isn‚Äôt confined to the rivers though, it‚Äôs spread far and wide under the land to create five large swamps in Lahemaa, a vast wetland area known as the capital of Estonian primeval nature.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Flood-meadows adjoin swamp forests, and bears live here, along with deer, elk, wild boar, beaver, lynx, and wolf - it feels truly prehistoric!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ AVOIDING THE PLAGUE üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You got to love the sense of humour. Tallinn's Old Town is one of the best preserved medieval cities in Europe. And medieval cities recall medieval problems!

The Bubonic plague - cause of the Black Death in the 14th Century - killed 50 million people, or around half the population of Europe.

Luckily today Estonian food can be enjoyed without any worries!Estonian cuisine is based on meat and potatoes, and on fish in coastal and lakeside areas, particularly rye bread, pork, potatoes and yoghurt.

My personal fave is Vastlakukkel, wheat buns filled with whipped cream and covered in powdered sugar.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ THE ISLE OF SAAREMAA üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The largest island of the Baltics, Estonia‚Äôs Saaremaa is home to just over 30,000, a rural paradise of spas and the immense castle at Kuressaare.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs also the gateway to Riga, Latvia, positioned like a blockade to the Gulf of Riga. So it makes sense to build a big lighthouse to stop ships bashing in to it!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
This is S√µrve Lighthouse at the tip of the 32km long S√µrve Peninsula. Built first in 1646 out of wood it‚Äôs been remade a few times, last succumbing to war in 1944 between the Russians and Germans. The present cone-shaped lighthouse of monolithic concrete was built in 1960. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ THE BEAUTIFUL FORTIFICATION üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Founded in 1260 Kuressaare Castle is one of the best Medieval fortifications in Europe and one of my favourite sites in all of the Baltics.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs located on the island of Saaremaa to the west of mainland Estonia and looks like a picture book castle, with its drawbridge, towers and moat. But the most unexpected element is its own beach!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The shady park around the castle moat was laid out in 1861 and there are some fine wooden resort buildings in and around it, notably the Spa Hall (Kuursaal) dating from 1899, which is now a restaurant, and a neighbouring bandstand from 1920. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ RUMMU - A MANMADE LANDSCAPE üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Rummu Prison just outside Tallinn was closed long ago - and quickly submerged under a lake, making for great diving. Next to it is this intriguing landscape - but can you guess how it came about?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs actually a quarry that was used as a mining site for Vasalemma marble (a kind of limestone) for a very long time.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Most of the workforce came from the detainees of prison, and rainwater has then eroded the mound to create odd shapes and provide a new habitat for vegetation that is now growing all over it.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

üá™üá™ ISLAND LIFE IN ESTONIA üá™üá™
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Welcome to the Baltics - three of Europe‚Äôs most curious little countries all snuggled together between Scandinavia, Russia, and Eastern Europe.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
This fabulous place, our favourite hotel stay in Estonia, is called Padaste, on the island of Muhu, right next to the much larger Saaremaa island.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
As usual I wanted to go far beyond the obvious stops to show what the rest of these countries have to offer, besides the capitals of Tallinn, Riga and Vilnius.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Padaste itself dates back to the 1400s, a glorious Manor House converted into a haven of peace, with a spa, yoga every morning and fine food, all surrounded by forest and with its own waterside jetty too. I bet it looks even better covered in snow!

Yep, it looks like the Maldives or Seychelles, but this jungle island is actually off the south coast of Cambodia!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Song Saa is an ethical luxury resort unlike any other I‚Äôve encountered, a perfect example of how to design a retreat and make a positive impact on the local community and environment.

The resort has its own @songsaafoundation that works to protect the habitats of the Koh Rong Archipelago, including establishing the Cambodian kingdom‚Äôs first marine reserve. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs my favourite place I stayed this year so I thought I‚Äôd share a few images in the coming days about this gem!

SAYING BYE TO SAUDI - MY TOP TIPS
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
A final post from my 3-week journey around Saudi Arabia last year, and time to share a few tips for those considering a visit!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- As anywhere - take your time! Saudi is a huge country with a lot to explore.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- Get on the road - driving is easy, roads are good, and yes, women can drive too.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- Stay local - couples can stay together even if they are not married, so try local hotels, and check out the camps in Al Ula
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- Get in touch with locals - Saudis are incredibly hospitable and welcoming. Jeddah for example, is a vibrant city for of cafes, restaurants and a great place to mingle with locals.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- Don‚Äôt be put off by politics - Yes, the government has been pretty awful in many things, but it‚Äôs changing fast, and locals aren‚Äôt afraid to discuss their opinions.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- Don‚Äôt take a drone though - these are now banned unless you apply for permission in advance.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
- My favourites - Jeddah for the spectacular Al-Balad historic district, Wadi Lajab for the grand canyons, and Jabal Aswad for its green terraces.
